<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="stakeholder-analysis">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ba</group>
    <domain>business-analyst</domain>
    <summary>Identify parties, map them on a 2x2 influence-vs-impact matrix, plan engagement per quadrant. Register stored as YAML in git; diffs become relationship history.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>stakeholder-management</tag>
      <tag>engagement</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>change-management</tag>
      <tag>risk-mitigation</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <updated>2026-05-01</updated>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Stakeholder Analysis</title>

    <summary>A six-step methodology that identifies all parties affected by or influencing a change initiative, maps them on a 2x2 influence-vs-impact matrix (Manage Closely / Keep Satisfied / Keep Informed / Monitor), documents individual needs, concerns, and communication preferences, plans engagement cadence per quadrant, and stores the register as a YAML file in git so diffs become the relationship history. The register is a living artifact refreshed at minimum quarterly.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Requirements gathered from the wrong people are incomplete or conflict-laden; missing a regulator, works council, or downstream API consumer invalidates downstream artifacts. IIBA BABOK v3 ch. 3 treats stakeholder engagement as a Knowledge Area because the cost of a missing stakeholder compounds across every subsequent BA activity. Requiring an `evidence:` field on every attitude assertion prevents the politeness-bias failure where everyone is classified as "supportive."</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Kickoff of any cross-functional initiative with more than five named parties (sponsor, SMEs, end users, regulator, vendor)</item>
        <item>Migration/replacement projects where end-user resistance is the dominant risk</item>
        <item>Regulated programs (HIPAA, GDPR, SOX, MDR) — the regulator is a mandatory stakeholder</item>
        <item>M&amp;A and reorg work where the political map is unstable; rerun the matrix every 2-4 weeks</item>
        <item>Pre-RFP/vendor-selection work where the buying committee has hidden influencers (security, procurement, legal)</item>
        <item>Triggered automatically when CHANGELOG or `stakeholders/register.yaml` has not been touched for 90 days on an active initiative</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo founder pre-PMF with fewer than three people involved — go directly to customer interviews</item>
        <item>Strictly internal engineering refactors with no business stakeholder change — RACI alone is sufficient</item>
        <item>Public open-source projects with anonymous community contributors — influence/impact axis is meaningless; use governance patterns</item>
        <item>One-off bug fixes or hotfixes — the stakeholder map will be stale before the deploy completes</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <how-to>
      <step>Step 1 — Seed inputs. Collect three artifacts before touching the register: (a) machine-readable org chart export (CSV with `name,title,manager,department`), (b) project charter or kickoff transcript, (c) any prior `stakeholders/register.yaml`. Refuse to proceed if (a) is missing — without it the agent will hallucinate names.</step>
      <step>Step 2 — Identify. For every named or implied party in the inputs, draft a register entry with eight-category classification (Customer, EndUser, Sponsor, DomainSME, ImplementationSME, Tester, Regulator, Supplier). Run the hidden-stakeholders sweep: legal, infosec, procurement, works council/union, accessibility, downstream API consumers. Anything not in the org chart goes to `suggested_to_verify:`, never to the register.</step>
      <step>Step 3 — Score influence and impact on a H/M/L scale; pick the quadrant. Apply Mitchell-Agle-Wood salience overlay (power × legitimacy × urgency) for politically sensitive initiatives and flag definitive stakeholders (all three) for daily attention.</step>
      <step>Step 4 — Capture attitude with evidence. Set `attitude` to `+|0|-|unknown` and require an `evidence:` array (quote, transcript line, ticket URL). Without evidence, attitude defaults to `unknown`, NEVER to `0`. Triangulate any `+` or `-` against at least one behavioural signal (meeting attendance, Slack response time, sponsor escalations, ticket comments).</step>
      <step>Step 5 — Plan engagement using the quadrant defaults: HH = weekly 1:1, HL = biweekly summary, LH = monthly digest, LL = release-only. Override only with explicit `override_reason:`.</step>
      <step>Step 6 — Commit a patch (≤5 changed entries per commit) to `stakeholders/register.yaml` with a one-line rationale, raise an MR, and request CODEOWNERS sponsor approval for any attitude transition out of `unknown` or for any new entry.</step>
    </how-to>

    <section name="identification">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always include a hidden-stakeholders review step covering: legal, infosec, procurement, works council/union, accessibility, and downstream API consumers. Missing a stakeholder is the dominant real-world failure mode.</statement>
        <rationale>Hidden stakeholders discovered after elicitation begins trigger scope changes, re-validation, and delayed sign-offs; finding them at step 1 costs a single conversation. BABOK v3 ch. 3 lists stakeholder identification as a Knowledge Area, not a preliminary task.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Eight stakeholder categories:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Customer — external beneficiary (end users, buyers, partners).</item>
        <item>End User — direct solution users (employees, customers).</item>
        <item>Sponsor — provides resources and authority (executive, budget owner).</item>
        <item>Domain SME — subject matter expert (process owner, specialist, regulator).</item>
        <item>Implementation SME — technical expert (developer, architect, integrator).</item>
        <item>Tester — validates the solution (QA team, UAT participants).</item>
        <item>Regulator — compliance authority (legal, audit, government body).</item>
        <item>Supplier — external provider (vendor, partner, outsourcer).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="influence-impact-matrix">
      <rule>
        <statement>Map every stakeholder to one of four quadrants and set default engagement cadence by quadrant: Manage Closely (HH) = weekly 1:1, Keep Satisfied (HL) = biweekly summary, Keep Informed (LH) = monthly digest, Monitor (LL) = release-only. Override only with explicit rationale.</statement>
        <rationale>Stakeholders managed at the wrong cadence either receive information overload (damaging the relationship) or feel ignored (creating resistance); quadrant-driven defaults calibrate engagement without requiring per-stakeholder judgment for every decision.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply the Mitchell-Agle-Wood salience overlay (power × legitimacy × urgency) on top of the matrix for politically sensitive initiatives; flag "definitive" stakeholders (all three) for daily attention.</statement>
        <rationale>The 2x2 matrix collapses multi-dimensional politics into one axis; salience theory adds urgency and legitimacy that explain why some low-title stakeholders have outsized influence.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="needs-concerns-engagement">
      <rule>
        <statement>Require an evidence: field on every attitude assertion (quote, transcript line, ticket link); without evidence, attitude defaults to "unknown," not "0" (neutral).</statement>
        <rationale>Self-reported attitude is unreliable; people say "supportive" in workshops and undermine in private. Evidence-backed attitude claims are actionable; ungrounded attitude claims are noise that produces wrong engagement strategies.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Triangulate self-reported attitude with at least one behavioral signal (meeting attendance, Slack response time, sponsor escalations, ticket comments) before assigning attitude to any high-influence stakeholder.</statement>
        <rationale>High-influence stakeholders whose actual attitude diverges from stated attitude are the most dangerous source of late-stage resistance; early triangulation enables proactive management.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="conflict-resolution">
      <rule>
        <statement>When two stakeholders have conflicting needs, follow this sequence: understand each position (why, not what) → find common ground → identify trade-offs → escalate to sponsor with options → document decision with rationale.</statement>
        <rationale>Conflicts resolved by position-trading ("you get requirement A, I get requirement B") without understanding underlying interests re-emerge during design and testing. Interest-based resolution produces durable agreements.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Conflict resolution techniques:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Facilitated workshop — for groups with multiple conflicting positions.</item>
        <item>One-on-one discussions — for sensitive interpersonal conflicts or political situations.</item>
        <item>Prototype/demo — to clarify misunderstandings caused by abstract requirements.</item>
        <item>Prioritization exercise — to force trade-off choices when all options cannot be delivered.</item>
        <item>Sponsor decision — for conflicts that exceed the BA's authority to resolve.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="git-native-register">
      <rule>
        <statement>Store the stakeholder register as YAML in git (stakeholders/register.yaml); subagents emit patches, never overwrite the register directly. Each transition (added, attitude shift, escalated) is committed with a one-line rationale.</statement>
        <rationale>git log -- stakeholders/ becomes the relationship history; git blame shows who reclassified whom; CODEOWNERS gates sponsor sign-off on attitude changes. A wiki or spreadsheet cannot provide any of these audit capabilities.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Refresh the register quarterly at minimum; set a calendar trigger that opens an issue assigned to the BA. In M&amp;A and reorg contexts, refresh every 2-4 weeks.</statement>
        <rationale>Stakeholder registers drift in 2-6 weeks in fast-moving organizations; a static register goes stale and becomes wrong, not just old. Automated refresh triggers prevent the register from becoming a liability.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never publish names + attitudes outside the BA and sponsor; treat the register as confidential. PII regulations (GDPR Art. 9) may apply if attitude implies political opinion or health status.</statement>
        <rationale>Attitude records about named individuals are sensitive personal data; public exposure damages relationships and may create legal liability in GDPR-jurisdiction projects.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="register-template">
      <p>Lift this YAML directly into `stakeholders/register.yaml`. Field order is significant for diff readability.</p>
      <example type="good" title="register.yaml — single entry">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[# stakeholders/register.yaml
version: 1
updated: 2026-05-01
owner: ba@example.com
entries:
  - id: S-01
    name: "Jane Doe"
    role: "VP Engineering"
    category: Sponsor          # Customer|EndUser|Sponsor|DomainSME|ImplementationSME|Tester|Regulator|Supplier
    influence: H               # H|M|L
    impact: H                  # H|M|L
    quadrant: ManageClosely    # ManageClosely|KeepSatisfied|KeepInformed|Monitor
    attitude: unknown          # +|0|-|unknown   (default: unknown)
    evidence: []               # required for + or -; list of quotes/links
    salience:                  # Mitchell-Agle-Wood, optional
      power: true
      legitimacy: true
      urgency: false
    engagement:
      cadence: "weekly 1:1"
      channel: "in-person"
      next_touch: 2026-05-08
    needs: []
    concerns: []
    last_reviewed: 2026-05-01
suggested_to_verify:
  - name: "<Legal counsel — name TBC>"
    reason: "GDPR Art. 9 review needed"]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <example type="good" title="Discovery prompt">
        <note>Constrains to real org chart entries, flags unknown attitudes, and surfaces hidden stakeholders as suggestions rather than entries.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are the stakeholder-discovery agent. Inputs:
1. Org chart snippet (names, titles, reporting lines).
2. Kickoff transcript / charter.
3. Existing register (may be empty).

For each named or implied party, emit STRICT JSON:
{ "id": "S-NN", "name": "...", "role": "...",
  "category": "Customer|EndUser|Sponsor|DomainSME|ImplementationSME|Tester|Regulator|Supplier",
  "influence": "H|M|L", "impact": "H|M|L", "attitude": "+|0|-|unknown",
  "evidence": ["quote or org-chart line"],
  "engagement": "Manage Closely|Keep Satisfied|Keep Informed|Monitor",
  "rationale": "<= 2 sentences" }

Rules: do not invent people. If attitude is not directly evidenced, return "unknown".
Flag potential hidden stakeholders (legal, infosec, works council, procurement,
downstream API consumers) in a separate suggested_to_verify list.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Engagement-plan prompt">
        <note>Uses quadrant mapping as default override policy.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Given the register below, produce the engagement table.
Quadrant mapping: HH=Manage Closely (weekly 1:1),
HL=Keep Satisfied (biweekly summary), LH=Keep Informed (monthly digest),
LL=Monitor (release notes only). Override only with explicit rationale.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Diff-review prompt (human-in-the-loop)">
        <note>Forces the agent to summarise risk before the BA approves the patch.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are reviewing a stakeholder register diff. For every changed entry,
output: id, change_type (added|removed|attitude|quadrant|engagement),
risk_level (low|medium|high), one-sentence justification.
Block the merge with status=NEEDS_HUMAN if any high-risk change has no
linked evidence or no sponsor sign-off.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <commands>
      <command name="bootstrap">mkdir -p stakeholders &amp;&amp; touch stakeholders/register.yaml</command>
      <command name="lint-yaml">python3 -c "import yaml,sys; yaml.safe_load(open('stakeholders/register.yaml'))" &amp;&amp; echo OK</command>
      <command name="quadrant-counts">python3 -c "import yaml; r=yaml.safe_load(open('stakeholders/register.yaml')); from collections import Counter; print(Counter(e['quadrant'] for e in r['entries']))"</command>
      <command name="missing-evidence">python3 -c "import yaml; r=yaml.safe_load(open('stakeholders/register.yaml')); [print(e['id']) for e in r['entries'] if e['attitude'] in ['+','-'] and not e.get('evidence')]"</command>
      <command name="staleness">git log -1 --format=%cs -- stakeholders/register.yaml</command>
      <command name="diff-history">git log --oneline -- stakeholders/register.yaml | head -20</command>
      <command name="render-matrix">python3 templates/stakeholder-matrix.py stakeholders/register.yaml &gt; docs/stakeholder-matrix.mmd</command>
      <command name="commit-patch">git add stakeholders/register.yaml &amp;&amp; git commit -m "stakeholders: update S-01 attitude unknown→+ (evidence: kickoff transcript L42)"</command>
    </commands>

    <checklist>
      <check>Org chart export (CSV) is on disk and referenced by the agent prompt.</check>
      <check>Every entry has a unique id of the form `S-NN`.</check>
      <check>Every entry has `category`, `influence`, `impact`, `quadrant`, `attitude`, `last_reviewed`.</check>
      <check>No entry has `attitude` of `+` or `-` without a non-empty `evidence` array.</check>
      <check>No entry was invented — every name appears in the source org chart, transcript, or charter.</check>
      <check>Hidden-stakeholder sweep ran: legal, infosec, procurement, works council, accessibility, downstream API consumers — each is either entered or in `suggested_to_verify`.</check>
      <check>Quadrant cadence matches the default unless `override_reason` is set.</check>
      <check>Salience overlay computed for any politically sensitive initiative.</check>
      <check>Patch contains ≤5 changed entries (bulk reclassification is forbidden).</check>
      <check>Sponsor (CODEOWNERS) approved any attitude transition out of `unknown`.</check>
      <check>`last_reviewed` ≤ 90 days for steady-state initiatives, ≤ 28 days for M&amp;A/reorg.</check>
      <check>Confidentiality: register file is not exposed in any public artifact, README, or wiki.</check>
    </checklist>

    <verify>
      <step>Run `python3 -c "import yaml; yaml.safe_load(open('stakeholders/register.yaml'))"` — must exit 0. Any YAML error blocks the merge.</step>
      <step>Run the `missing-evidence` command above — output must be empty (no `+`/`-` attitudes without evidence).</step>
      <step>Run the `quadrant-counts` command and inspect the distribution; if &gt;70% of stakeholders fall into one quadrant, the matrix has degenerated and scoring should be revisited.</step>
      <step>Run `git diff --stat stakeholders/register.yaml` — must show ≤5 entries changed in this commit; if more, split into multiple commits.</step>
      <step>Run `git log -1 --format=%cs -- stakeholders/register.yaml`; confirm freshness against the cadence rule (90/28 days).</step>
      <step>Generate the Mermaid quadrant chart with `templates/stakeholder-matrix.py` and visually confirm there are no unlabeled or duplicate names.</step>
      <step>For any new entry or attitude transition, confirm the MR carries an approving review from a CODEOWNERS sponsor.</step>
      <step>Grep the repo for accidental leakage: `git grep -nE "attitude:\s*[+-]"` outside `stakeholders/` must return zero matches.</step>
    </verify>

    <section name="ai-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent invents plausible-sounding stakeholders ("VP of Product Excellence") not present in the org chart.</description>
        <reason>Hallucinated stakeholders produce engagement plans with no real recipients; always seed with a real org chart export and reject any name not in the source list unless flagged suggested_to_verify.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent over-classifies all stakeholders as "supportive" (politeness bias).</description>
        <reason>LLMs are trained on polite discourse and default to positive sentiment; use a 4-way enum (+/0/-/unknown) with unknown as the default and require evidence for + or -.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent conflates stakeholder with persona ("As a Busy Manager persona...").</description>
        <reason>A stakeholder is a real named human or role with decision power; a persona is a synthesized archetype for design. Conflating them produces engagement plans targeting archetypes, not real people with authority.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent equates influence with seniority — ranks CFO highest influence by default.</description>
        <reason>Influence flows through indirect networks; the CFO's EA may have more influence on calendar decisions than the CFO. Force the agent to consider gatekeepers, information brokers, and informal leaders, not just org chart level.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent bulk-reclassifies 50 stakeholders in a single run.</description>
        <reason>Bulk reclassification of attitude fields is reputationally toxic if wrong; cap agent actions to 5 stakeholders per run and require human review on the diff.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="human-in-the-loop">
      <rule>
        <statement>Require human approval at three points: adding a new stakeholder, changing attitude from unknown to positive or negative, and escalating a conflict to sponsor. Agent prepares the patch; BA or sponsor approves the merge.</statement>
        <rationale>Stakeholder relationship decisions have political consequences; automated execution without human sign-off can damage trust, violate confidentiality expectations, and create legal liability.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <list>
        <item>The 2x2 influence/impact matrix flattens multi-dimensional politics — power, urgency, and legitimacy (Mitchell-Agle-Wood salience) are collapsed into one axis and important nuance is lost.</item>
        <item>Stakeholder lists drift fast (2–6 weeks in fast-moving orgs); a static register goes stale and becomes wrong, not just old. README mistake #5 is the dominant real-world failure.</item>
        <item>Hidden stakeholders (works councils, legal, infosec, procurement, downstream consumers of an API) are systematically missed — agents will not invent them unless given org-chart context.</item>
        <item>Self-reported attitude is unreliable — people say "supportive" in workshops and undermine in private. The matrix only works if attitude is triangulated against behaviour.</item>
        <item>LLM hallucinates plausible-sounding personas ("VP of Product Excellence") that do not exist in the target org; outputs must be validated against an actual directory / org chart.</item>
        <item>Cultures vary: in high-context cultures (JP, KR) influence flows through indirect networks the matrix does not represent.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-register.md" purpose="Stakeholder register table with ID, role, category, influence, impact, attitude, engagement columns."/>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-profile.md" purpose="Individual stakeholder profile with characteristics, needs, concerns, communication preferences, engagement history."/>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-matrix.py" purpose="Script: validate YAML register and emit Mermaid quadrant chart for influence-vs-impact visualization."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.iiba.org"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
